== Textbooks and references

There is no textbook. Everything we'll use will be posted on the this webpage in pdf format.

If you’d like to consult some books, we listed some below.

- [https://mitpress.mit.edu/9780262013192/probabilistic-graphical-models /Probabilistic Graphical Models: Principles and Techniques/], Daphne Koller and Nir Friedman (2009)
- [https://probml.github.io/pml-book/book2.html /Probabilistic Machine Learning: Advanced Topics/], Kevin P. Murphy (2023)
- [https://link.springer.com/book/10.1007/978-3-030-61943-5 /Probabilistic Graphical Models: Principles and Applications (2nd edition)/], Luis Enrique Sucar (2021)
- [http://bayes.cs.ucla.edu/BOOK-2K /Causality (2nd edition)/], Judea Pearl (2009)
- [https://bayes.cs.ucla.edu/PRIMER/ /Causal Inference in Statistics: A Primer/], Judea Pearl (2016)

== Prerequisites

There are no strict prerequisites, but good knowledge of probability would significantly reduce the learning curve.
Exposure to graph theory, optimization, and reinforcement learning helpful but not required.

== Final exam

The final exam is a 90 minutes open-book exam.
You are allowed to bring one cheat sheet subject to the following requirements:

- The cheat sheet could be (at most) one double sided A4 paper.
- The content must be hand-written.
- Yes, you could write digitally and then print, but a magnifier is not allowed in the exam.

No other materials (e.g., textbooks) are allowed in the exam.
We will confirm if a calculator is strictly necessary closer to the exam date, but you can nevertheless bring one as you like.

